description:
This series, sometime called "the V.th series", was published by Edifumetto from July 1981 to September 1985, and is the continuation of "Zora La Vampira" series. Zora nuova serie, comparing to its predecessor, has a more explicit drawing, in line with the new Italian editorial laws of those years.

The series includes 68 numbers and 4 supplements (#1suppl. - Festa di sangue, #54suppl. - La sorella del mostro, #65suppl. - Vietato rubare cadaveri). For tax reasons, in September 1983, what should have been #12 of the volume "Necron" comes out, instead, as a supplement to Zora nuova serie #44 (#44suppl. - NECRON - Sopraffatta dai mostri).

In April 1986, Zora has one new story as a supplement to the series "Fasma" (Fasma #7suppl. - Divorarti il cuore).

Strangely enough, the French edition of Zora has the last 12,5 stories specially made for the French market ("Zara la Vampire", ending of #130 until #142), unreleased in Italy and drawn by a different artist. After this, we have to wait until 1999 ("Collana Evoluzioni" published by Lennoxx) before reading two new stories of our beautiful vampire, that had little success and didn't have the announced sequel.
name: Zora Nuova Serie

Here, the issues are proposed with a sequential numbering for the 3 series: the original number and series are listed by parenthesis (for example, 25 / III means number 25 of the III.rd series).
 
For the first series, Edifumetto published 36 issues from 1993 to 1997; for the second series, 5 issues in 1998; for the third series, 26 issues from 2001.

description:
The Kilroys issue #1 was first published by American Comics Group under their imprint B & I Publishing in 1947.

The Kilroys with the tag line 'America's Funniest Family!' was a comic book version of the family situation comedy that was currently popular on the radio and television at that time. The Kilroy family consisted of: the father J. Edgar Kilroy, his wife Emmy and their children Natch and Katie along with the family dog, Bumpy.

The stories in The Kilroys were aimed at the teen market and featured both the family as a whole and also as individuals. The issue had a comparatively long run ending with the final issue #54 in July 1955.
name: Kilroys

description:
A Machiavellian undertone turns what might have been a run-of-the-mill shojo title into an interesting and unsettling study of just how much children—and, by extension, adults—judge books by their covers. Three boys using the name the Scissors Project give highly coveted makeovers to "ugly" girls at their school: "in the hands of those three, a girl becomes beautiful... she gets the guy of her dreams...." But first-year student Kiri, herself talented with a pair of scissors, doesn't care for the way they manipulate girls into subservience. While the boys of the Project continue to rule the school, a mysterious figure begins giving "magical" makeovers in secret, threatening the Project's power; this leads to an inevitable showdown battle, with scissors replacing swords, and an even more inescapable cliffhanger. The book's visual design is appropriately elegant and pretty, with lots of open panels and atmospheric, graphical elements—and it polarizes the world of the story into sharply drawn halves, the pretty characters very pretty, the ugly ones very ugly. Young readers may have trouble discerning where the vapid shallowness ends and the satire begins—if in fact it does. The message does indeed seem to be that beauty matters above all, and the only thing left to determine is how best to acquire it. (Sept.)
